40|$|This article {{poses the}} question: Now {{that women are}} {{receiving}} an increasing share of the seats on the Supreme Court of Canada (the Court), can we conclude with confidence {{that they have been}} admitted to full participation, with a mix of judgments—including the more significant decisions—that is fully comparable to their male colleagues? The author looks at the assignment of <b>reasons</b> <b>for</b> <b>judgment</b> on the Court over the last three chief justiceships, with specific reference to the relative rate of assignments to male and female judges. He finds that the male/female gap is more robust than ever, although he also identifies considerations that suggest that there may be factors other than gender alone that are at play...|$|R
